itational name from Arcy in Manche, France, with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘from’.","Irish: in Ireland, this is generally the Norman name (see 1 above), established in Meath by Sir William <i>D'Arcy</i> in the 1360s, but it was also adopted for <b>Ó Dorchaidhe</b> ‘descendant of the dark one’, from <i>dorcha</i> ‘dark, gloomy’, a Connacht name that fell together with the Norman surname, which was introduced by Sir William <i>D'Arcy</i> and Sir John <i>D'Arcy</i>, Chief Justiciar of Ireland in the 14th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Darsey","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Darcy   2.","Scottish: from Dairsie in Fife."]},{"name":"Darcey","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and Irish (Tipperary): variant of   Darcy  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Darcy was born in 1480, in Connaught, Ireland. She married Sir James FitzGerald of Leixlip about 1527, in Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1527, in Cork, County Cork, Ireland, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1480–1527":"1480–1527","1491–1537":"1491–1537","1505–1581":"1505–1581","1581":"1581","1480":"1480","1491":"1491","Abt 1527":"umbes 1527","1505":"1505","1527":"1527","1537":"1537","Falghe, Connaught , Kildare, Ireland":"Connaught, Iirimaa","Dromana, Waterford, Ireland":"County Waterford, Iirimaa","Plattyn, Meath, Ireland":"Iirimaa","Cork, Ireland":"Cork, County Cork, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1480–1527":"1480–1527","1491–1537":"1491–1537","1505–1581":"1505–1581","1581":"1581","1480":"1480","1491":"1491","Abt 1527":"noin 1527","1505":"1505","1527":"1527","1537":"1537","Falghe, Connaught , Kildare, Ireland":"Connaught, Irlanti","Dromana, Waterford, Ireland":"County Waterford, Irlanti","